^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well, that was a good illustration of a squeeze. Let me discuss the play first, then the auction. The first 3 tricks were fine. At trick four, however, because briatt knows moe started with 5 hearts, she should realize that South is out of hearts. Her best chance is to try and cash the Q of diamonds. As I have said, it is important that you take clues from the auction to help you figure out what declarer has. Once she didn't do that, diane now has squeeze possibilities to make her contract. diane has a diamond loser. If clubs are 3-3, then she can pitch her diamond on the last club.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, there is another possibility, which happen to work on this hand. If the person with 4 clubs also has the Q of diamonds, then diane can squeeze that person by running all her spades, east has to come down to 4 cards and it is impossible for east to both hold 4 clubs and the Q of diamonds. As that requires her to have 5 cards, and there are only 4 cards left after the spades are played. That is an example of a "squeeze", where one defender is not able to protect 2 suits. When you have all the tricks but one, it is a good idea to run all your winners, because it is often difficult for the defenders to discard correctly.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As for the bidding,  up through 2@S, everything is fairly normal. One could make a case that briatt should bid 4@H. Technically that is the correct bid. however, there are tactics to consider. East does not want to push N/S into 4@S, so 3@H might work out better, just enough to push them to 3@S but not enough to push them to makable 4. It turns out, with my singleton heart and six card spade suit, I will bid 4 anyway, but east doesn't know that for sure. By the law of total tricks, since East have at least a 10 card fit, 4@H is a safe bid. It turns out they make 4@H. This is a good example of how distribution and fits matter.|
