^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|OK, first the bidding. I like all the bids through 3@C. In match points, it is a good bid for moe to bid 3@S because -50 or -100 is better than -110. However, in imps it is not that good a bid.  He only has 5 spades, and not a singleton club, so more often than not it will not turn out well.  3@S is down one if they find the diamond ruff. On the other hand briatt  would lead a club and it is likely 3@S would make if diane fails to shift to a diamond after cashing AQ of clubs. Now as to diane's 4@C bid. On the plus side, she has a singleton spade and 6 pretty good clubs. On the minus side, she is vulnerable, and partner did not support clubs. So, on balance, I think pass is better.|
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to the play. My only comment is, on the trick seven (first heart), diane should play low. It turns out I will play the J from AJ, but some defenders might make a mistake and put up the ace. Since she has 2 sure heart losers, she can always play the king the 2nd time the suit is led  so might as well play low the first time.  On this hand it doesn't make a difference, but it might on some hands.|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


AT|
vanyvon: Please explain why you make a difference between imps and Match Points for the 3@s bid by moe? |
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|imps is based on your actual score. so -100 and -110 are essentially the same score. So, the idea in imps is to go plus on a part score hand. However, in match points, you get one point for everyone you beat, regardless of the score. If you score -100 and they can score -110 for making 3@C, you do much better with your -100, because you beat every pair who let them score -110. Even a 10 point difference is important in match points. Match Points is much harder to judge, particularly part scores  because the size of your score matters. In imps, if you are plus on a part score hand, that is usually sufficient.|
