^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his important @E@3instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls"  which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you can find many more.

|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||CP||AT|New suits by responder are always forcing. So, as long as responder keeps bidding a new suit, opener cannot pass.  The reason for that is, typically, responder is "captain" of the hand and more often than not, responder decides the final contract. Therefore, responder needs a way to keep the bidding open to determine what the best contract is. However, the same is not true of opener. A new suit by opener is not forcing. When opener has a game forcing hand (18+), their rebid must be a jump shift or jump to 2N to establish the game force.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|If partner opens a weak 2, and you have 3 card support and are sure you don't want to go to game, just bid 3, since you have a 9 card fit. This is known as "furthering the preempt" which makes it much harder for the opponent to bid.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|Bid more aggressively when you have a fit with partner (high cards in his suits) and shortness in opponents suit, less aggressively with misfits (high cards in opponents suit, shortness in partner's suit.)
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|Almost all the time, when I lead low from Qxx, assuming my partner has not bid the suit, it does not work out well. I am not sure why that is, but it seems to be true. So I try to avoid leading from Qxx unless there really is no other choice.



  
